Thread explicit set-autolisp-errno calls through every failing
IO / entity / selection builtin.

Status: open
Baseline: claude/system-variables @ f4d5503
Parent : issues/open/system-variables.issue (Phase 3, item 3)
Spec   : autolisp-spec/documentation/autolisp-visual-lisp-specification-draft.org
         §15 *Errors and Recovery* + §16 ~System Variable Entry: ERRNO~

== Context ==

Phase 3 (commit f4d5503) put the ERRNO bridge in place: ~(getvar
"ERRNO")~ now reads the live runtime-session slot via
~clautolisp.autolisp-runtime:autolisp-errno~, and the
SET-AUTOLISP-ERRNO helper has been in the runtime since long
before this work started.

What is NOT done -- and what this follow-up addresses -- is the
per-builtin wiring: Autodesk's reference documents many file IO,
entity, and selection builtins as "returns nil and sets ERRNO" on
failure, but our implementations of those builtins currently return
nil without touching ERRNO. The bridge means a user-level
~(getvar "ERRNO")~ *can* observe an ERRNO value, but in practice
the value never changes because nothing sets it.

Concretely, ~clautolisp/autolisp-builtins-core/source/api.lisp~
references ~set-autolisp-errno~ in 5 places today (all inside
~builtin-vl-catch-all-apply~). Every other failure path that should
set ERRNO simply returns nil.

== Scope ==

The list below names every builtin whose vendor documentation
states "returns nil and sets ERRNO" or an equivalent phrase. Each
needs:

  1. The matching SET-AUTOLISP-ERRNO call at the failure site.
  2. A SET-AUTOLISP-ERRNO 0 call on the success path (Autodesk
     docs are explicit that ERRNO is reset on a successful call).
  3. A unit test asserting both the nil return AND the ERRNO
     value after the failure, plus the ERRNO=0 reset after a
     subsequent success.

The ERRNO code table the spec implies (sources cited inline; the
full mapping must be validated against AutoCAD 2026 ENU before it
lands):

  ERRNO=0  No error / reset on success.
  ERRNO=1  Misc. error / invalid argument.
  ERRNO=2  Invalid filename / file not found.
  ERRNO=3  File-system error (open failed, write failed).
  ERRNO=4  Attempted file write in read-mode handle.
  ERRNO=5  Bad / out-of-range integer argument.
  ERRNO=6  Bad / out-of-range real argument.
  ERRNO=7  Bad / out-of-range string argument.
  ERRNO=8  Reserved.
  ERRNO=9  Invalid list / dotted-pair structure.
  ERRNO=10 Invalid point (not a 2- or 3-list of reals).
  ERRNO=11 Invalid entity name (ENTGET/ENTMOD/ENTDEL etc.).
  ERRNO=12 Operation on deleted entity.
  ERRNO=13 Attempt to mutate a closed selection set.
  ERRNO=14 Invalid selection-set object.
  ERRNO=51 Bad symbol-table name passed to TBLSEARCH / TBLNEXT.
  ERRNO=52 XDATA / regapp problem.
  ERRNO=60 Bad XDSIZE list shape.

Verify the table against
  https://help.autodesk.com/view/ACD/2026/ENU/?guid=GUID-ERRNO
(GUID covered by autolisp-spec inventory; see the per-sysvar
:source field for ERRNO -- AutoCAD URL has the canonical list).

== Builtins to wire ==

Grouped by category. Codes are the ones from the table above; if
a category has a single applicable code it's noted in parentheses.

=== File / IO (codes 2, 3, 4) ===

  open                       (cannot open / file in wrong mode)
  close                      (already-closed file)
  read-line                  (read past EOF on closed stream)
  read-char                  (read past EOF / closed stream)
  write-line                 (write to read-mode handle)
  write-char                 (write to read-mode handle)
  findfile                   (file not found -> 2)
  findtrustedfile            (file not found OR not trusted -> 2)
  load                       (file not found / parse error -> 2/3)
  vl-file-copy               (source missing / dest unwritable)
  vl-file-delete             (file missing -> 2)
  vl-file-rename             (source missing / dest exists)
  vl-file-size               (file missing -> 2)
  vl-file-systime            (file missing -> 2)
  vl-file-directory-p        (path missing -> 2)
  vl-directory-files         (directory missing -> 2)
  vl-filename-mktemp         (cannot create temp -> 3)
  vl-mkdir                   (mkdir failed -> 3)

=== Entity access (codes 11, 12) ===

  entget                     (invalid / deleted ename)
  entmod                     (invalid ename or DXF list)
  entmake / entmakex         (bad DXF list -> 9; invalid ename -> 11)
  entdel                     (already deleted -> 12; missing -> 11)
  entupd                     (missing -> 11)
  entlast                    (no entities -> nil with ERRNO=0)
  entnext                    (last entity -> nil with ERRNO=0)
  handent                    (bad handle string -> 11)
  nentsel / nentselp         (selection canceled -> 0; missing -> 11)
  entsel                     (selection canceled -> 0)
  acdimenableupdate          (no AcDim) -- verify on docs

=== Selection sets (codes 13, 14) ===

  ssget                      (filter rejects / no selection -> 0)
  ssadd                      (bad ename -> 11; bad sset -> 14)
  ssdel                      (member missing -> 11; bad sset -> 14)
  ssname                     (out-of-range -> 5; bad sset -> 14)
  sslength                   (bad sset -> 14)
  ssmemb                     (bad sset -> 14)
  ssgetfirst / sssetfirst    (bad sset -> 14)

=== Symbol tables & dictionaries (codes 51, 52) ===

  tblsearch / tblnext / tblobjname  (bad kind/name -> 51)
  namedobjdict               (no docroot -> 11)
  dictsearch / dictnext / dictadd / dictremove / dictrename
                             (bad dict ename -> 11; bad name -> 51)

=== XDATA / regapp (codes 52, 60) ===

  xdsize                     (bad list / unregistered app -> 52/60)
  xdroom                     (bad ename / unregistered app -> 11/52)
  regapp                     (already registered -> 0; bad name -> 7)

== Method ==

1. For each builtin in the list, locate its DEFUN in
   ~clautolisp/autolisp-builtins-core/source/api.lisp~ (or its
   companion files where extracted -- ~file-io.lisp~,
   ~entity-api.lisp~, etc.).

2. Wrap the failure path so it does:

     (clautolisp.autolisp-runtime:set-autolisp-errno N)
     nil

   instead of bare ~nil~. Where the failure path is implicit
   (the function falls through to a HANDLER-CASE on an
   underlying CL error), wire SET-AUTOLISP-ERRNO inside that
   handler.

3. Add the matching successful-call reset:

     (clautolisp.autolisp-runtime:set-autolisp-errno 0)
     <return-value>

   in the body of each builtin's success path. (Per Autodesk
   docs ERRNO is reset on any successful AutoLISP call --
   verify this is uniform.)

4. Cross-link the wiring to the inventory: in each affected
   builtin's docstring or comment, cite the inventory record
   it implements (e.g. ~;;; Inventory: ERRNO -- AutoCAD 2026
   GUID-...~).

5. Conformance tests live in
   ~clautolisp/autolisp-builtins-core/tests/~ (currently ~900
   checks). Add per-builtin failure-and-success ERRNO checks
   beside the existing return-value tests; the shape is:

     (test builtin-NAME-sets-errno-2-on-missing-file
       (clautolisp.autolisp-runtime:reset-default-evaluation-context)
       (is (null (builtin-findfile (make-autolisp-string "/no/such"))))
       (is (eql 2 (clautolisp.autolisp-runtime:autolisp-errno))))

== Acceptance criteria ==

  - [ ] The ERRNO code table above is verified against AutoCAD
        2026 ENU and BricsCAD V25 docs (per-sysvar :source URLs
        in the inventory) and committed as a normative table in
        autolisp-spec §15 ~Errors and Recovery~.
  - [ ] Every builtin in the scope list above sets ERRNO on
        failure and resets it on success.
  - [ ] Every builtin in the scope list has a paired
        failure-and-success ERRNO test.
  - [ ] ~grep -c 'set-autolisp-errno'~ in
        autolisp-builtins-core/source/api.lisp rises from 5
        (Phase 3 baseline) to roughly the count of builtins in
        scope * 2 (one set + one reset per builtin).
  - [ ] The full conformance-test bundle (autolisp-test) is
        green.

== Risks / open questions ==

  - The ERRNO code values are partly conventional and Autodesk's
    own reference is incomplete. Some codes will need direct
    probing against AutoCAD 2026 / BricsCAD V25 to confirm.
    BricsCAD ships its own subset of ERRNO codes; divergences
    must land in the inventory's ~:divergence~ field for ERRNO.
  - On successful calls, AutoCAD may or may not reset ERRNO --
    confirm against the live products before committing the
    "reset on success" branch. If reset behaviour varies by
    builtin, the spec must say so.
  - ~set-autolisp-errno~ requires an evaluation context to be
    bound. Some builtins are called outside an explicit context
    (REPL toplevel, etc.) -- the helper must no-op cleanly in
    that case.

== Out of scope ==

  - Live AutoCAD / BricsCAD backends (Phase 16) will need their
    own ERRNO mapping from engine error codes to our normative
    table. That's a Phase-16 concern, not this issue's.
  - DIESEL / menucmd error handling is not part of ERRNO; it
    has its own error-code path.

